<section class="section-panel" id="s-redesign-services">
<div class="wrap">
  <div class="rd-hero">
    <div class="rd-eyebrow">Section 5.4 · Service Integration · Document Redesign Framework</div>
    <h1>Enterprise Document Redesign &amp; <em>Optimization Framework</em></h1>
    <p>This section integrates the uploaded service-options framework into the UAAD masterplan as a practical operating standard for professional report redesign: how to structure complex information, govern AI-assisted production, control security risk, and verify accessibility before publication.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="rd-snapshot" aria-label="Redesign framework snapshot">
    <div class="rd-snap-card"><b>01</b><span>Structure before style: executive summaries, navigable tables of contents, findings, discussion, recommendations, and appendices.</span></div>
    <div class="rd-snap-card"><b>02</b><span>Readable systems: consistent styles, sufficient white space, clear hierarchy, and color choices that are not the only carrier of meaning.</span></div>
    <div class="rd-snap-card"><b>03</b><span>Governed AI workflow: pilots, data audits, model-risk controls, hallucination review, and human approval gates.</span></div>
    <div class="rd-snap-card"><b>04</b><span>Compliance by design: WCAG, Section 508, ADA Title II, alt text, semantic structure, and tested contrast.</span></div>
  </div>

  <div class="rd-note">
    <p><strong>Integration premise:</strong> document redesign is treated as an information-delivery architecture, not surface decoration. The report should help readers process strategy quickly, preserve attribution, reduce AI and data risk, and remain usable by readers with disabilities.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="rd-grid">
    <div class="rd-card">
      <div class="rd-card-kicker">Report architecture</div>
      <h2>Convert the report into a decision-ready artifact</h2>
      <p>The service framework distinguishes essays from professional reports: reports must transmit objective intelligence through a stable structure. For this UAAD report, the redesign standard is:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Lead with the executive case and bottom-line recommendation.</li>
        <li>Use section-level wayfinding for leadership review.</li>
        <li>Separate data presentation from interpretation and action.</li>
        <li>Use appendices for supporting evidence that would interrupt the main narrative.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="rd-card accent">
      <div class="rd-card-kicker">Visual hierarchy</div>
      <h2>Use hierarchy, not decoration, to improve comprehension</h2>
      <p>The report should rely on consistent heading styles, neutral card systems, structured tables, readable spacing, and repeatable section patterns. Color should support hierarchy, never substitute for labels, values, or explanatory text.</p>
      <p><span class="rd-pill">Styles</span><span class="rd-pill">White space</span><span class="rd-pill">Table clarity</span><span class="rd-pill">Readable labels</span></p>
    </div>
    <div class="rd-card safe">
      <div class="rd-card-kicker">Attribution</div>
      <h2>Protect credibility with source discipline</h2>
      <p>The framework emphasizes a two-part citation system: in-text attribution and a corresponding reference list. For UAAD reporting, every public metric, benchmark, AI-generated synthesis, and external design principle should be traceable to its source or clearly labeled synthetic.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rd-card warn">
      <div class="rd-card-kicker">Accessibility</div>
      <h2>Build WCAG checks into the redesign workflow</h2>
      <p>Final reports should include semantic headings, descriptive alt text for visuals, meaningful labels, non-color-only status indicators, and contrast-checked text. Accessibility is treated as a release requirement, not a post-production fix.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="section-heading" style="font-size:1.35rem;margin-top:30px">Redesign Service Operating Model</h2>
  <div class="section-rule"></div>
  <div class="rd-flow" aria-label="Redesign service workflow">
    <div class="rd-step"><span class="rd-step-num">Step 01</span><strong>Diagnose</strong><span>Audit structure, audience, purpose, data sources, broken CSS, and accessibility gaps.</span></div>
    <div class="rd-step"><span class="rd-step-num">Step 02</span><strong>Architect</strong><span>Define report spine, executive summary, section map, evidence flow, and appendix strategy.</span></div>
    <div class="rd-step"><span class="rd-step-num">Step 03</span><strong>Redesign</strong><span>Apply neutral business visuals, table hierarchy, cards, tabs, charts, and print-friendly surfaces.</span></div>
    <div class="rd-step"><span class="rd-step-num">Step 04</span><strong>Govern</strong><span>Validate AI outputs, citations, data lineage, security posture, and human approval gates.</span></div>
    <div class="rd-step"><span class="rd-step-num">Step 05</span><strong>Verify</strong><span>Run contrast, readability, mobile, print, citation, and accessibility checks before release.</span></div>
  </div>

  <div class="rd-table-wrap">
    <table class="rd-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Service Option</th><th>Best Use in This Report</th><th>Governance Requirement</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Executive business report redesign</td><td>Turn the masterplan into a leadership-ready portfolio with rapid navigation and clear decision points.</td><td>Maintain objective claims, source notes, consistent sections, and a stable appendix.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>AI-assisted content and slide generation</td><td>Use AI to accelerate summaries, outlines, and visual alternatives without replacing expert review.</td><td>Require data audits, hallucination checks, prompt-injection awareness, and approval gates.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Brand and layout system</td><td>Use a neutral business design suite with no dark-background conflicts and repeatable cards/tables.</td><td>Lock core styles, avoid manual one-off formatting, and test contrast after every theme change.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Security and risk management</td><td>Map risks such as model poisoning, hallucinated metrics, prompt injection, and disclosure of confidential material.</td><td>Use NIST AI RMF, ISO 42001-style controls, STRIDE categories, audit logs, and role-based permissions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Accessibility compliance</td><td>Ensure the HTML report is readable, navigable, and adaptable for users with visual, motor, cognitive, or assistive-technology needs.</td><td>Apply WCAG 2.1 AA principles, Section 508/ADA expectations, alt text, semantic markup, and contrast checks.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="rd-grid">
    <div class="rd-card">
      <div class="rd-card-kicker">AI platform fit</div>
      <h2>Use the right generation tool for the output</h2>
      <p>The source framework compares AI presentation tools by speed, governance, creative flexibility, and export fidelity. For a report like this:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Gamma</strong> is strongest for rapid web-native ideation and draft structure.</li>
        <li><strong>Beautiful.ai</strong> is strongest for brand-governed, team-ready decks.</li>
        <li><strong>Canva</strong> is strongest for marketing-oriented creative assets.</li>
        <li><strong>ChatSlide / native PowerPoint tools</strong> are useful when editable PPTX output fidelity matters.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="rd-card safe">
      <div class="rd-card-kicker">Risk controls</div>
      <h2>Operationalize review before distribution</h2>
      <p>Every AI-assisted redesign should pass a release checklist covering factuality, source attribution, confidentiality, prompt-injection exposure, accessibility, and final visual QA. This is especially important for documents containing donor, pipeline, financial, or institutional strategy content.</p>
      <p><span class="rd-pill">Data lineage</span><span class="rd-pill">Human review</span><span class="rd-pill">Audit log</span><span class="rd-pill">Alt text</span><span class="rd-pill">Contrast</span></p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="rd-table-wrap">
    <table class="rd-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Release Check</th><th>Pass Standard</th><th>Why It Matters</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Structure</td><td>Sections follow a clear executive-to-evidence flow and navigation matches the report body.</td><td>Prevents leaders from hunting for the decision logic.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Data integrity</td><td>All metrics are either sourced, synthetic-labeled, or removed.</td><td>Reduces reputational and compliance risk.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>AI verification</td><td>Generated summaries and tables are checked against source material.</td><td>Prevents hallucinated claims or invented figures.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Accessibility</td><td>Headings, tables, contrast, labels, and visual alternatives are tested.</td><td>Supports WCAG-aligned, legally safer distribution.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Theme stability</td><td>Legacy dark backgrounds, low-contrast fills, and broken CSS rules are removed or overridden.</td><td>Ensures the suite remains professional, readable, and maintainable.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>
